{{Infobox academic | honorific_prefix = | name = Grant R. Osborne | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = Grant R. Osborne.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Osborne with class after delivering final lecture before retiring | birth_name = <!-- Use only if different from full/othernames --> | birth_date = {{birth date|1942|07|07|mf=yes}} | birth_place = Queens, New York City, NY | death_date = {{death date and age|2018|11|04|1942|07|07|mf=yes}} | death_place =Libertyville, Illinois | death_cause = | region = | nationality = American | period = | occupation = [[Theologian]] and [[New Testament]] scholar | title = Professor of New Testament at [[Trinity Evangelical Divinity School]] | boards = <!-- Board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation --> | known_for = | spouse = | children = | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | era = | language = | discipline = Biblical hermeneutics<!-- Major academic discipline - e.g. Physicist, Sociologist, New Testament scholar, Ancient Near Eastern Linguist --> | sub_discipline = New Testament studies<!-- Academic discipline specialist area - e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist --> | movement = <!-- Should match the idiologial movement or denomination (for religious), "school" of thought etc. (e.g. "Anglican", "Postmodernist", "Socialist" or "Green" etc. --> | religion = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | denomination = <!-- Religious denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | education = | alma_mater = [[Aberdeen University]] (PhD)<!-- will often consist of the linked name of the last-attended higher education institution. --> | thesis_title = History and Theology in the Resurrection Narratives: A Redactional Study | thesis_url = | thesis_year = 1974 | doctoral_advisor = [[I. Howard Marshall]] | doctoral_students = | notable_students = <!--Only those with WP articles--> | main_interests = | workplaces = <!--full-time positions only, not student positions--> | notable_works = ''The Hermeneutical Spiral'' | notable_ideas = | influences = <!--Must be referenced from a third party source--> | influenced = <!--Must be referenced from a third party source--> | awards = <!--Notable national level awards only--> | website = | footnotes = }} '''Grant R. Osborne''' (July 7, 1942 &ndash; November 4, 2018)<ref>[https://www.patheos.com/blogs/jesuscreed/2018/11/04/grant-osborne/ Grant Osborne]</ref> was an American [[theologian]] and [[New Testament]] scholar. He was Professor of New Testament at [[Trinity Evangelical Divinity School]].
Osborne had degrees from [[Fort Wayne Bible College]], [[Trinity Evangelical Divinity School]], and the [[University of Aberdeen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Grant R. Osborne, PhD|url=http://divinity.tiu.edu/academics/faculty/grant-r-osborne-phd/|publisher=[[Trinity Evangelical Divinity School]]|accessdate=27 November 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029232737/http://divinity.tiu.edu/academics/faculty/grant-r-osborne-phd/|archivedate=29 October 2014|df=}}</ref>
Osborne specialised in [[biblical hermeneutics]]. He is best known for his concept of the "hermeneutical spiral",<ref>{{cite book|last1=Melick|first1=Richard R.|title=In Defense of the Bible: A Comprehensive Apologetic for the Authority of Scripture|chapter=Can We Understand the Bible?|date=2013|page=114|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ChpkAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA114|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref> denoting an "upward and constructive process of moving from earlier pre-understanding to fuller understanding, and the returning back to check and to review the need for correction or change in this preliminary understanding."<ref>{{cite book|last1=Thiselton|first1=Anthony C.|title=Hermeneutics: An Introduction|date=2009|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oDI6FrROli4C&pg=PA14|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref>
Osborne was a member of the Bible Translation Committee for the ''Holy Bible:'' [[New Living Translation]]. He served as General Translator for the Gospels and Acts.<ref>See the list of translators in any copy of the New Living Translation.</ref>
