'''Rupert Clendon Lodge''' (1886–1961) was an Anglo-Canadian philosopher, "the most widely read of all philosophers in Canada".<ref>Elizabeth A. Trott, [http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/rupert-clendon-lodge/ Lodge, Rupert Clendon], ''[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]''.</ref>
Lodge was born in [[England]], but spent most of his academic career at the [[University of Manitoba]], where he taught from 1920 to 1947. [[Marshall McLuhan]] was a student of Lodge in the early 1930s.<ref>[http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/people/lodge_rc.shtml Memorable Manitobans: Rupert C. Lodge (1886-1961)], citing J. M. Bunsted, ''Dictionary of Manitoba Biography'', University of Manitoba Press, 1999.</ref>
