{{Slavic Native Faith}}
'''[[Slavic Native Faith]]''' (Rodnovery) has a [[theology]] that is generally [[monism|monistic]], consisting in the vision of an [[absolute (philosophy)|absolute]], supreme [[God]] (''[[Rod (Slavic religion)|Rod]]'') who begets the universe and ''lives'' as the universe ([[pantheism]] and [[panentheism]]), present in all its phenomena. [[Polytheism]], that is the worship of the gods or spirits, and ancestors, the facets of the supreme Rod generating all phenomena, is an integral part of Rodnovers' beliefs and practices.

The ''[[swastika]]''-like ''kolovrat'' is the symbol of Rodnovery.{{sfn|Pilkington|Popov|2009|p=282}} According to the studies of [[Boris Rybakov]], whirl and wheel symbols, which also include patterns like the "six-petaled rose inside a circle" (e.g. [[File:RozetaSolarSymbol.svg|30px]]) and the "thunder mark" (''gromovoi znak''), represent the supreme Rod and its various manifestations (whether [[Triglav]], [[Svetovid]], [[Perun]] or other gods).{{sfn|Ivanits|1989|pp=14, 17}}

==Theological stances==
[[File:Sylenkoite representation of Rod.png|thumb|Icon of the highest God (Rod) in human shape, in a Sylenkoite temple in Ukraine.]]

===Monism and polytheism: Rod and deities===
{{Further|Rod (Slavic religion)|Deities of Slavic religion}}
Prior to their Christianisation, the Slavic peoples were [[polytheism|polytheists]], worshipping multiple deities who were regarded as the emanations of a supreme [[God]]. According to [[Helmold]]'s ''[[Chronica Slavorum]]'' (compiled 1168–1169), "obeying the duties assigned to them, [the deities] have sprung from his [the supreme God's] blood and enjoy distinction in proportion to their nearness to the god of the gods".{{sfn|Rudy|1985|p=5}} Belief in these deities varied according to location and through time, and it was common for the Slavs to adopt deities from neighbouring cultures.{{sfn|Shnirelman|2017|p=89}} Both in Russia and in Ukraine, modern Rodnovers are divided among those who are [[monotheism|monotheists]] and those who are polytheists;{{sfnm|1a1=Lesiv|1y=2013|1p=90|2a1=Aitamurto|2y=2016|2p=65|3a1=Shnirelman|3y=2017|3p=90}} in other words, some emphasise a unitary principle of divinity, while others put emphasis on the distinct gods and goddesses.{{sfn|Laruelle|2008|p=290}} Some Rodnovers even describe themselves as [[atheism|atheists]],{{sfn|Shnirelman|2017|p=102}} believing that gods are not real entities but rather ideal symbols.{{sfn|Shizhenskii|Aitamurto|2017|p=109}}

[[File:The Seven Gods -- Maxim Sukharev.jpg|thumb|left|''The Seven Gods''—Russian artist Maxim Sukharev, 2010s. The artwork represents the supreme God (Rod) manifested as a sevenfold hierarchy, according to Slavic theo-cosmology.{{refn|group=note|''The Seven Gods'', by Russian Rodnover artist Maxim Sukharev, represents the seven major deities of Slavic theo-cosmology, together constituting the hierarchy emanating from the supreme God (Rod). The elements of the drawing are the following ones:<br>

① The [[axis mundi|central axis]] is Svarog ("Heaven"), comprising his three forms: the four-faced Svetovid ("Worldseer"), Perun ("Thunder") at the very centre, and Svarozhich ("Son of Heaven") below. Further below Svarozhich there is another form of he himself contained in a squared receptacle, Ognebog ("Fire God").<br>

② On the right and left hand of Svetovid there are, respectively, Belobog ("White God") and Chernobog ("Black God"), themselves in the guise of Dazhbog ("Day God") and Jutrobog ("Moon God"). They are the supreme polarity upon which all the alternating ways of divine manifestation rely.<br>

③ To the left and to the right of the white figure of Perun, there are, respectively, the black figure of the great goddess Mokosh/Mat Syra Zemlya ("Wetness/Damp Mother Earth") and the red figure of Veles (the male god belonging to the Earth and god of tamed animals).<br>

④ The three forms of Svarog and the three gods Perun, Veles and Mokosh constitute intersecting trinities (Triglav, Tribog), which correspond to the three dimensions: Prav, Yav and Nav. Prav, literally "Right", is ultimately the central axis of Heaven itself, functioning as the medium of all dimensions of space-time. In the guise of thunder (Perun) it impregnates matter (Mokosh), which retains its rhythmic squaring regulations (thus constituting Nav, which is the continuity of time); in the guise of the Son of Heaven it comes to light in present reality (Yav), and is fostered by humanity (Veles), and preserved as the hearth (Ognebog).}}]]

Monotheism and polytheism are not regarded as mutually exclusive. The shared underpinning is a [[pantheism|pantheistic]] view that is [[holism|holistic]] in its understanding of the universe.{{sfn|Shnirelman|2017|p=102}} Similarly to the ancient Slavic religion, a common theological stance among Rodnovers is that of [[monism]], by which the many different gods (polytheism) are seen as manifestations of the single, universal God—generally identified by the concept of ''Rod'',{{sfn|Aitamurto|2016|p=65}} also known as ''Sud'' ("Judge") and ''Prabog'' ("Pre-God", "First God") among [[South Slavs]].{{sfn|Mathieu-Colas|2017}}

In the Russian and Ukrainian centres of Rodnover theology, the concept of Rod has been emphasised as particularly important.{{sfn|Aitamurto|2006|p=188}}{{sfn|Lesiv|2017|p=142}} The root *''rod'' is attested in sources about pre-Christian religion referring to divinity and ancestrality.{{sfn|Aitamurto|2006|p=188}}{{sfn|Pilkington|Popov|2009|p=288}} Mathieu-Colas defines Rod as the "primordial God", but the term also literally means the generative power of the family and "kin", "birth", "origin" and "fate" as well.{{sfn|Mathieu-Colas|2017}} Its negative form, ''urod'', means something wrenched, deformed, degenerated, monstrous.{{sfn|Aitamurto|2016|p=65}} Sometimes, the meaning of the word is left deliberately obscure among Rodnovers, allowing for a variety of different interpretations.{{sfn|Aitamurto|2006|p=188}} The Russian [[volkhv]]s [[Veleslav]] (Ilya Cherkasov) and Dobroslav (Aleksei Dobrovolsky) explain Rod as a life force that comes in nature and is "all-pervasive" or "omnipresent".{{sfn|Aitamurto|2016|p=65}}

====Manifestationism====
[[File:Slavic divine hierarchy, Creuzer-Mone 1822.jpg|thumb|350px|Hierarchy of the divine, with the two categories proceeding from the supreme God, as illustrated by [[Georg Friedrich Creuzer|Georg F. Creuzer]] and [[Franz Mone|Franz J. Mone]].{{sfn|Creuzer|Mone|1822|p=197}} All deities are manifestations of either Belobog or Chernobog, and in both categories they may be either ''Razi'', rede-givers, or ''Zirnitra'', dragon wizards.{{sfnm|1a1=Creuzer|1a2=Mone|1y=1822|1pp=195–197|2a1=Heck|2y=1852|2pp=289–290}}]]
Cosmologically speaking, Rod is conceived as the spring of universal [[emanationism|emanation]], which articulates in a cosmic hierarchy of gods.{{sfn|Rabotkina|2013|p=240}} When emphasising this monism, Rodnovers may define themselves as ''rodnianin'', "believers in God"{{sfn|Pilkington|Popov|2009|p=269}} (or "in nativity", "in genuinity"). Already the pioneering Ukrainian leader Volodymyr Shaian argued that God manifests as a variety of different deities.{{sfn|Lesiv|2013b|p=130}}

This theological explanation is called "manifestationism" by some contemporary Rodnovers, and implies the idea of a spirit–matter continuum; the different gods, who proceed from the supreme God, generate differing categories of things not as their external creations (as objects), but embodying themselves as these entities. In their view, beings are the progeny of gods; even phenomena such as the thunder are conceived in this way as embodiments of these gods (in this case, [[Perun]]).{{sfn|Aitamurto|2016|p=66}} In the wake of this theology, it is common among Slavic Native Faith practitioners to say that "we are not God's slaves, but God's sons".{{sfn|Aitamurto|2006|p=188}} Some Rodnover groups espouse the idea that specific Slavic populations are the sons of peculiar facets of God; for instance, groups who rely upon the tenth-century manuscript ''The Lay of Igor's Host'' may affirm the idea that Russians are the grandchildren of [[Dazhbog]] (the "Giving God", "Day God").{{sfn|Aitamurto|2006|p=188}}

A Russian Rodnover leader, Nikolai Speransky ([[volkhv]] Velimir), emphasises a [[dualistic cosmology|dualistic]] eternal struggle between forces of [[good and evil]]; the former represented by [[Belobog]] ("White God"), who created the human soul, and the latter by [[Chernobog]] ("Black God"), who created the human body.{{sfn|Shnirelman|2017|p=93}} They are the twofold dynamism through which the supreme God expresses its spirits, taking part in the characteristics of both categories.{{sfn|Heck|1852|pp=289–290}}

====Clusters of deities====
[[File:Northwestern Slavic divine hierarchy, Hanuš 1842.jpg|thumb|350px|Northwestern Slavic hierarchy of the divine, as illustrated by Ignác Jan Hanuš.{{sfn|Hanuš|1842|p=182}}]]
Pantheons of deities are not unified among practitioners of Slavic Native Faith.{{sfn|Laruelle|2008|pp=289–290}} Different Rodnover groups often have a preference for a particular deity over others.{{sfn|Laruelle|2008|p=290}} The Union of Russian Rodnover Communities founded and led by Vadim Kazakov recognises a pantheon of over thirty deities emanated by the supreme Rod;<ref name="Adversus paganos">{{cite magazine |last1=Belov |first1=Maxim |last2=Garanov |first2=Yuri |date=10 February 2015 |title=Adversus Paganos |publisher=Journal of the Ascension Cathedral of Astrakhan |website=astrsobor.ru |url=http://astrsobor.ru/adversus-paganos-novaya-istoriya-protiv-yazychnikov/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523191143/http://astrsobor.ru/adversus-paganos-novaya-istoriya-protiv-yazychnikov/ |archive-date=23 May 2017 |access-date=7 July 2017}}</ref> these include attested deities from Slavic pre-Christian and folk traditions, Slavicised Hindu deities (such as ''Vyshen'', i.e. [[Vishnu]], and ''Intra'', i.e. [[Indra]]), Iranian deities (such as [[Simargl]] and Khors), deities from the ''[[Book of Veles]]'' (such as Pchelich), and figures from Slavic folk tales such as the wizard [[Koschei]].{{sfn|Shnirelman|2017|p=95}} Rodnovers also believe and worship [[tutelary deity|tutelary deities]] of specific elements, lands and environments,{{sfn|Aitamurto|2006|p=204}} such as waters, forests and the household. Gods may be subject to functional changes among modern Rodnovers; for instance, the traditional god of livestock and poetry [[Veles (god)|Veles]] is called upon as the god of literature and communication.{{sfn|Aitamurto|2016|p=66}}

===Sylenko's monotheism===
In Ukraine, there has been a debate as to whether the religion should be monotheistic or polytheistic.{{sfn|Lesiv|2013a|p=90}} In keeping with the pre-Christian belief systems of the region, the groups who inherit Volodymyr Shaian's tradition, among others, espouse polytheism.{{sfn|Lesiv|2013a|p=90}} Conversely, Lev Sylenko's [[Native Ukrainian National Faith]] (RUNVira for short, called "Sylenkoism" in some academic scholarship) regards itself as monotheistic and focuses its worship upon a single God whom they identify by the name Dazhbog.{{sfnm|1a1=Ivakhiv|1y=2005c|1p=225|2a1=Lesiv|2y=2013a|2p=90|3a1=Lesiv|3y=2013b|3p=130}} For members of this group, Dazhbog is regarded as the life-giving energy of the cosmos.{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005c|p=225}}

Sylenko characterised Dazhbog as "light, endlessness, gravitation, eternity, movement, action, the energy of unconscious and conscious Being".{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005c|p=225}} Based on this description, Ivakhiv argued that Sylenkoite theology might better be regarded as [[pantheism|pantheistic]] or [[panentheism|panentheistic]] rather than monotheistic.{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005c|p=225}} Sylenko acknowledged that the ancient Ukrainian-Rus were polytheists but believed that a monotheistic view reflected an evolution in human spiritual development and thus should be adopted.{{sfn|Lesiv|2013a|p=91}} A similar view is adopted by Russian [[Ynglism]].{{sfn|Aitamurto|2016|p=66}} Lesiv recorded one RUNVira member who related that "we cannot believe in various forest, field and water spirits today. Yes, our ancestors believed in these things but we should not any longer".{{sfn|Lesiv|2013a|p=92}} For RUNVira members, polytheism is regarded as backward.{{sfn|Lesiv|2013a|p=92}} Some polytheist Rodnovers have regarded the approach adopted by Sylenko's followers as an inauthentic approach to the religion.{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005c|p=223}}

==Cosmology==
[[File:Black and White. Suprematist Composition (Malevich, 1915).png|thumb|''Black and White. Suprematist Composition''—[[Kazimir Malevich]], 1915. According to Miroslav Shkandrij, the Russian [[Suprematism|Suprematist]] artist was influenced by a dual cosmology found in various folk beliefs, including Belobog and Chernobog.<ref>Shkandrij, Miroslav. "[http://shron.chtyvo.org.ua/Myroslav_Shkandrij/Reinterpreting_Malevich_Biography_Autobiography_Art_anhl.pdf Reinterpreting Malevich: Biography, Autobiography, Art]". ''Canadian-American Slavic Studies''. '''36''' (4). pp. 405–420. (see p. 415).</ref>]]

===Dual dynamism: Belobog and Chernobog===
According to the ''Book of Veles'', and to the doctrine accepted by many Rodnover organisations, the supreme Rod begets ''Prav'' (literally "Right" or "Order"; cf. Greek ''[[Orthotes]]'', Sanskrit ''[[Ṛta]]'') in primordial undeterminacy ([[chaos (cosmogony)|chaos]]), giving rise to the circular pattern of [[Svarog]] ("Heaven", "Sky"; cf. Sanskrit ''[[Svarga]]''), which constantly multiplies generating new worlds (world-eggs). Prav works by means of a dual dynamism, represented by Belobog ("White God"{{sfn|Mathieu-Colas|2017}}) and Chernobog ("Black God"{{sfn|Mathieu-Colas|2017}}); they are two aspects of the same, appearing in reality as the forces of waxing and waning, giving rise to polarities like up and down, light and dark, male and female, singular and plural. Man and woman are further symbolised by father Svarog itself and mother [[Lada (goddess)|Lada]].{{sfn|Rabotkina|2013|p=240}}

This supreme polarity is also represented by the relation between Rod and ''Rozanica'', literally the "Generatrix", the mother goddess who expresses herself as the three goddesses who interweave destiny (''Rozanicy'', also known as ''Sudenicy'' among South Slavs, where Rod is also known as Sud, "Judge").{{sfn|Mathieu-Colas|2017}} She is also known as ''Raziwia'', ''Rodiwa'' or simply ''Dewa'' ("Goddess"), regarded as the singular goddess of whom all lesser goddesses are manifestations.{{sfn|Hanuš|1842|pp=135, 281}} In kinships, while Rod represents the forefathers from the male side, Rozanica represents the ancestresses from the female side. Through the history of the Slavs, the latter gradually became more prominent than the former, because of the importance of the mother to the newborn child.{{sfn|Máchal|1918|p=249}}

===The three qualities of reality and the ''axis mundi''===
====Triglav====
[[File:Triglav scheme.svg|thumb|Scheme of Triglav's cosmology.]]
{{Main|Triglav (mythology)}}
In duality, the supreme Rod's luminous aspect (Belobog) manifests ultimately as threefold, ''Triglav'' ("Three-Headed One"{{sfn|Mathieu-Colas|2017}}). The first of the three persons is the aforementioned Svarog ("Heaven"), and the other two are Svarog's further expressions as Perun ("Thunder") and Svetovid (the "Worldseer", itself four-faced). They correspond to the three dimensions of the [[cosmos]], and to the three qualities of soul, flesh and power. Svarog represents Prav itself and soul, Perun represents ''Yav'' and flesh, and Svetovit represents ''Nav'' and spiritual power.{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=8, note 35}}

According to Shnirelman, this triune vision and associations were codified by Yuri P. Mirolyubov and further elaborated by Valery Yemelyanov, both interpreters of the ''Book of Veles''.{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=8, note 35}} In olden times, already [[Ebbo]] documented that the Triglav was seen as embodying the connection and mediation between Heaven, Earth and the underworld.{{sfn|Dynda|2014|p=60}} [[Adam of Bremen]] described the Triglav of [[Wolin (town)|Wolin]] as ''Neptunus triplicis naturae'' (that is to say "[[Neptune (mythology)|Neptune]] of the three natures/generations") attesting the colours that were associated to the three worlds, then further studied by [[Karel Jaromír Erben]]: white for Heaven, green for Earth and black for the underworld.{{sfn|Dynda|2014|p=63}} Other names of the two manifestations of Svarog are Dazhbog ("Giving God", "Day God") and Svarozhich (the god of fire, literally meaning "Son of Heaven").{{sfn|Mathieu-Colas|2017}} According to the studies of Jiří Dynda, the three faces of Triglav are rather Perun in the heavenly plane (instead of Svarog), Svetovid in the centre from which the horizontal four directions unfold, and Veles in the underworld.{{sfn|Dynda|2014|pp=74–75}} The netherworld, especially in its dark aspect, is indeed traditionally embodied by Veles, who in this function is the god of waters but also the one who guides athwart them in the function of [[psychopomp]] (cf. Sanskrit ''[[Varuna]]'').{{sfn|Dynda|2014|p=72}}

In his study of Slavic cosmology, Dynda compares this ''[[axis mundi]]'' concept to similar ones found in other [[Proto-Indo-Europeans|Indo-European]] cultures. He gives weight to the Triglav as a representation of what [[Georges Dumézil]] studied as the "Indo-European [[trifunctional hypothesis]]" (holy, martial and economic functions reflected by three human types and social classes).{{sfn|Dynda|2014|p=63}} The Triglav also represents the interweaving of the three dimensions of time, metaphorically represented as a three-threaded rope.{{sfn|Dynda|2014|p=74}} By Ebbo's words, the Triglav is ''summus deus'', the god representing the "sum" of the three dimensions of reality as a mountain or tree (themselves symbols of the ''axis mundi'').{{sfn|Dynda|2014|p=64}} In a more abstract theoretical formulation, Dynda says that the three (Triglav) completes the two by springing out as the middle term between the twosome (Belobog and Chernobog), and in turn the threesome implicates the four (Svetovid) as its own middle term of potentiality.{{sfn|Dynda|2014|p=75}}

====Svetovid====
[[File:Svetovid scheme.svg|thumb|Scheme of Svetovid's cosmology.]]
{{Main|Svetovid}}
Svetovid ("Worldseer", or more accurately "Lord of Power" or "Lord of Holiness", the root *''svet'' defining the "miraculous and beneficial power", or holy power){{sfnm|1a1=Mathieu-Colas|1y=2017|2a1=Rudy|2y=1985|2p=18}} is the four-faced god of war and light, and "the most complete reflection of the Slavic cosmological conception", the union of the four horizontal directions of space with the three vertical tiers of the cosmos (Heaven, Earth and the underworld), and with the three times.{{sfn|Dynda|2014|p=75}} [[Helmold]] defined Svetovid as ''deus deorum'' ("god of all gods");{{sfn|Dynda|2014|p=59, note 9}} Dynda further defines Svetovid, by [[Carl Jung|Jungian]] words, as a "fourfold (''quaternitas'') potentiality which comes true in threefoldness (''triplicitas'')".{{sfn|Dynda|2014|p=75}} His four faces are the masculine Svarog ("Heaven", associated to the north direction and the colour white) and Perun ("Thunder", the west and red), and the feminine [[Mokosh]] ("Wetness", the east and green) and Lada ("Beauty", the south and black). The four directions and colours also represent the four Slavic lands of original sacred topography.{{refn|group=note|The four faces of Svetovid, the four colours and four directions, also correspond to the four Russias of folk cosmology: [[White Ruthenia]], [[Red Ruthenia]], the [[Black Sea]] regions and [[Green Ukraine]]. See: ''Svetovid'' in the ''Ukrainian Soviet Encyclopedic Dictionary'', 1987.}} They also represent the spinning of the four seasons.{{sfn|Leeming|2005|p=369: ''Svantovit''}}

Ultimately, Svetovid embodies in unity the supreme duality (Belobog and Chernobog) through which Rod manifests itself as Prav, and the axial interconnection of the three times with the four dimensions of present space. In other words, he represents Prav spiritualising Yav as Nav; or Svarog manifesting as spirit (Perun) in the material world governed by Veles. Dynda says that this conception reflects a common Indo-European spiritual vision of the cosmos, the same which was also elaborated in early and medieval Christianity as God who is at the same time creator (father), creature (son) and creating activity (spirit).{{sfn|Dynda|2014|p=76}}

===Prav, Yav and Nav—Heaven, Earth and humanity===
[[File:The Three Worlds (Heaven, Earth and humanity in-between) -- Maxim Sukharev.jpg|thumb|''The Three Worlds''—Maxim Sukharev, 2010s. Prav, Yav and Nav are represented, respectively, in the guise of Svarog ("Heaven") on the left, Mat Syra Zemlya ("Damp Mother Earth" who retains the squared rhythms of Heaven) on the right, and the "Son of Heaven" (Svarozhich), that is to say conscious humanity, as a medium in-between the two.]]

====Cosmology of the ''Book of Veles''====
{{Main|Prav-Yav-Nav}}
According to the ''Book of Veles'', reality has three dimensions, namely the aforementioned ''Prav'', ''Yav'' and ''Nav''.{{sfn|Shnirelman|2017|p=101}} Prav ("Right") itself is the level of the gods, who generate entities according to the supreme order of Rod; gods and the entities that they beget "make up" the great Rod. Yav ("actuality") is the level of matter and appearance, the here and now in which things appear in light, coalesce, but also dissolve in contingency; Nav ("probability") is the thin world of human ancestors, of spirit, consisting in the memory of the past and the projection of the future, that is to say the continuity of time.{{sfn|Rabotkina|2013|p=240}} Prav, the universal cosmic order otherwise described as the "Law of Heaven", permeates and regulates the other two hypostases.{{sfnm|1a1=Ivakhiv|1y=2005b|1p=202|2a1=Ivakhiv|2y=2005c|2p=230}}{{sfnm|1a1=Laruelle|1y=2008|1p=290|2a1=Aitamurto|2y=2016|2pp=66–67}}

====Lozko's genotheism and the worship of ancestors====
In her theological commentaries to the ''Book of Veles'', Ukrainian Rodnover leader [[Halyna Lozko]] betones the cosmological unity of the three planes of Heaven, Earth and humanity between them. She gives a definition of Rodnover theology and cosmology as "genotheism". God, hierarchically manifesting as different hypostases, a multiplicity of gods emerging from the all-pervading force Svarog, is genetically (''rodovid'') linked to humanity. On the human plane God is incarnated by the kin or lineage, in the Earth. Ethics and morality ultimately stem from this cosmology, as harmony with nature is possible only in the relationship between an ethnic group and its land.{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005a|p=23}}

This is also the meaning of the worship of human ancestors, whether the Slavs' general forefather ''Or'' or ''Oryi'',{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005a|p=14, cites ''Or''}} or local forefathers such as ''Dingling'' worshipped by [[Vladivostok]] Rodnovers.{{sfn|Shnirelman|2007|p=54, cites ''Oryi'' and ''Dingling''}} Divine ancestors are the spirits who generate and hold together kins, they ''are'' the kins themselves. The Russian [[volkhv]] Dobroslav emphasises the importance of blood heritage, since, according to him, the violation of kinship purity brings about the loss of the relationship with the kin's divine ancestor.{{sfn|Shnirelman|2007|p=54–55}} Ukrainian Rodnover and scholar Yuri Shylov has developed a theory of God as a spiral "information field" that expresses itself in self-conscious humanity, which comes to full manifestation in the [[Proto-Indo-European|Indo-European]] "Saviour" archetype.{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005a|p=23}}

