'''Étienne Chauvin''' (18 April 1640 – 6 April 1725),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.bnf.fr/13517101/etienne_chauvin/ |title=Étienne Chauvin (1640-1725)|publisher=Bibliotheque nationale de France}}</ref> [[France|French]] [[Protestant]] [[Anglicanism#Anglican divines|divine]], was born in [[Nîmes]]. At the revocation of the [[Edict of Nantes]] he retired to [[Rotterdam]] where he was for some years preacher at the [[Walloons|Walloon]] church; in 1695 the elector of [[Brandenburg]] appointed him pastor and professor of philosophy, and later inspector of the French college at [[Berlin]], where he enjoyed considerable reputation as a representative of [[René Descartes|Cartesianism]] and as a student of [[physics]]. His principal work is a laborious ''Lexicon Rationale, sive Thesaurus Philosophicus'' (Rotterdam, 1692; new and enlarged edition, Leeuwarden, 1713). He also wrote ''Theses de Cognitione Dei'' (1662), and started the ''Nouveau Journal des Savants'' (1694–1698).

